<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-9-25">
  <title>Resources for 9/25</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Given a quadratic function in any form, determine the <em>vertex</em>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Given a quadratic function in any form, determine at what values of <m>x</m> the function is zero. This includes factoring methods and the <em>quadratic formula</em>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Given a quadratic function, determine whether it opens up or opens down.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Given an applied problem involving a quadratic function, use your understanding of quadratic functions to interpret the function and make predictions.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use solution methods of quadratic equations to solve applied problems involving quadratic functions.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-vertex-quadratic-2">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Finding the Vertex of a Quadratic Function</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on finding the <em>vertex of a quadratic function</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="NCIzbXO0Z7w" />

    <problem>
      <title>Applications of Quadratic Functions</title>
      <p>
        You stand on a ledge 10 ft above the ground and throw a ball up in the air.  The height of the ball at time <m>t</m> seconds is <m>h(t) = -16t^2+32t+10</m> feet.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              At what time does the ball hit the ground?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              At what time does the ball reach its maximum height?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              What is the maximum height of the ball?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Optional Reading</title>
    <p>
      Section 1.5: pp. 51-58
    </p>
    <p>
      Here is a link for the <url href="https://activecalculus.org/prelude/sec-changing-quadratic.html">HTML version of Section 1.5</url>.
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>